Can you say more about what "fail" means?What error message are you getting, etc.Also, can you say more about the system you arerunning?  You said it was Linux 2.6.9 but didn'tsay what distribution.  Most Linux distributions"customize" the kernel settings or code, which isthe main reason binaries work in one place butnot others.The .interp section is a text string.Both these interp sections have the same bytes:    2f 6c 69 62 36 34 2f 6c 64 2d 6c 69 6e 75 78    2d 78 38 36 2d 36 34 2e 73 6f 2e 32 00which spells out    /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2The problem is likely somewhere else.Russ

I thinkthere maybe something wrong in the initial part of binary load.I just don't know how to dig it deeper. Can you give me someinstruction to  find out the possible problem ?I also find there is some problem when go try to open file not atlocal disk. I wonder if you have tried Go one NFS?(My company use EMC, which I think is very stable one).System detail:cat /etc/redhat-releaseRed Hat Enterprise Linux AS release 4 (Nahant Update 6)The spec of the machine is .AS4 (64-bit)    2.6.9-67.ELsmp  IntXeon 2.93G, RAM72G
If you have an older build of the code, you might be hitting:http://code.google.com/p/go/issues/detail?id=47In short: Red Hat Enterprise might be preventing mapping of W+X pages.AGL
